segments.text: We are talking about the freeway system.
And I bound again in a few licks here about signing and about the creation of anxiety levels.
And I wanted to mention for the record the difference, apparent difference, not just because I'm a planner, but I think just because I'm a motorist, in going from, say, a Houston to a San Diego.
and using the freeway systems there in the two cities, or even Los Angeles.
In Los Angeles, for example, the signing is very anticipatable in the sense that each exit is announced three times.
And the first time it's announced, it's at the bottom.
The second time, it's at the middle.
And then when you, the next time you are at the exit, it's at the top.
And all exits

are from the right hand lane unless it has been physically impossible because of historic problems to do otherwise and left hand exits are necessitated but it's a pattern that's exhibited all over the state of California and you come to expect that so you know you have three warnings before you ever have to make your maneuver and not only that but the signs are illuminated at night in all cases

and the splits for off-ramps and so forth are eliminated before you get to them, and the signs are placed well in advance so that you don't have to make an instant judgment at the moment of truth before you make your action maneuver.
And I believe that, personally, this creates a very low anxiety level and it contributes to the safety of the use of the freeway system.

There's one other thing I'd like to mention in connection with freeway design in urban areas, and that is its appearance in terms of relationship between man-made construction and the use of plant materials.
Of course, California is blessed with a certain climate that
enables things to stay green and flowering throughout the year, at least in the southern part of the state.

But even in the northern part of the state, where they have frosts and snow and so forth, there is an attempt made to put plant materials there that are native, require low maintenance, and that contribute to a kind of a softness of the sometimes necessarily harsh man-made constructions in terms of cuts
and bridge structures and so forth.
And I really would like to see something done more along those lines throughout Texas, but particularly in the urban areas such as Houston.
Well, I think we'll see those things.
I think with reference to the signing, I'm surprised.
note there's any great difference because the interstate system has the one set of design standards that apply nationwide.
Presumably.

Presumably and certainly I would look for uniform design standards throughout a state and apparently you've noted difference in the signing of Houston and Dallas and other Texas cities so apparently there's more
freedom left to the local district offices within the State Highway Department, and I'm aware of it.

Of course, it's well to remember that when the interstate highway system had its beginnings, the choice of the State Highway Commission in Texas was to concentrate in the urban areas first, rather than, say, city or states like Oklahoma and Florida that I'm familiar with
where they immediately moved into the rural areas because they could get more miles faster, and quite frankly, needed them more.
Their roads built in the 30s were really frightful to take care of the traffic of the early 50s.
So those states that had poor highways moved into the rural areas.
Texas, with a very excellent highway department over the years, had a very excellent rural system, and they immediately moved into the urban areas.
And in each urban area, as I understand it, is established an expressway office to design and coordinate construction, the awarding of contracts, et cetera, inspections.
For the, I think, one in Dallas, one in Fort Worth, one in Austin, one in San Antonio, one in Houston.
I think the urban expressway office in Houston is
of those state highway offices.
But even so, I thought they had a higher level of uniformity than they do.
Let me give you another example.
The freeway bypass for Bryan and College Station has on and off ramps, which by the admission of some people in the Texas Transportation Institute are a total disaster.
Which makes it even worse is the fact that the local
highway district engineers don't realize that there's any need for completely rebuilding them.
Is College Station in District 12 operates out of...
Okay, now let's proceed on, Roscoe, to... Do you perceive any administrative change within the planning department?
That's 11.
I don't see any at this time.
I'm not contemplating making any internal changes within the department.
Has the city, since you've been the planning director, made use of the work of planning consultants?
Very seldom.
We had a planning consultant
Actually, an architecture firm in the preparation of community shelters.
Master plan, which was a federally funded project.
And the growth options project in which Rice Center came in.
But most of the planning work the department over the years has been with personnel at the department.
OK.

these influences that are listed here political religious ethnic geographic sociological economic and military I think we've more or less covered as we've been going along but the city has now the problem of having expanded geographically over so much area 525 some square miles I believe that
The view now, particularly in view of energy concerns, is turning inward again.
And there has been a lot of discussion about the third ward and the role of the third ward and the fourth ward in the city.
Would you care to comment on that or any expansion of this concept?
Well, certainly, the

aging of housing in neighborhoods is becoming a much greater problem than it was say 10 years ago and receiving a much higher level of attention both in cap improvements and planning efforts and policy concerns.
I would hesitate to

say that there is a great movement into the central city of course we're currently under a sur moratorium that would restrict at least some of the developers and landowners feel like they're restricted from creating as high a density of developments as they would like when those restrictions are lifted with completion of the north east plant
we probably will see more density development in the eastern half of downtown.
The western half, I'm sorry, where there is a viable market for more dense housing.
In the eastern half, the growth options study indicated very few pressures for

extensive growth and development quite contrary there is need for a lot of revitalization and a lot of upgrading of housing it's going to be hard to come by at the same time the older areas on the east half represent a very good stock of housing in many respects Houston has
facetiously had the wisdom to build in this century instead of the previous one.
Therefore, we are not plagued with six-story cold-water tenement flats as New York and Chicago.
We're not faced with the high-density areas that have become slums that were built in the 1880s and such.
The close-in areas of Houston are suburban in character.
which means that there's a lot of close in areas that, given a stabilized confidence in these areas, can remain as good housing areas for many, many years.
There's been a lot of private rehabbing going on in Houston, as I understand it.
Is this making very much of an impact on the whole housing stock?
I think it would be hard to find in the statistics.
There's no question what old houses have been refurbished, but I think these are very few compared to the totality of the housing stock.
But there is definitely remodeling going on, rehabilitation going on in many areas close in.

And to some extent, like in, as in other cities, that the very success of the program, or I really can't call it program, the very success of the many individual investors, either as homeowners or as literally speculative investors in remodeling and reconditioning houses, has tended to drive the property up.
The desire of people to live close in with the energy prices and traffic congestion is driving the prices up to where there's a limit to how the market that can afford some of the close in areas.
You are the director of a large planning agency and as such you are of course responsible for the
performance of the professional planners on your staff and in that respect you are of course concerned about the quality of planning education that these individuals receive before they come to you.
In taking a look at perhaps your own experience with planning education and what's happened subsequently
Your thoughts on this would be appreciated.
Well, we were just talking between the tapes there on some aspects of this.
I shared with you some of the

questioning perhaps that the older one gets, the more nostalgic they get about their own education and the days that they spend at the university, particularly in graduate work, become a sort of golden age.
Certainly, the late 40s and 50s, for planning education, there was a very limited number of planning schools.
a very limited number of planning students, a very lucrative expanding job market for planners, and I think the quality of planning education during those days was really at a very high level.
The faculty members tended to be practitioners, very successful in the planning field,
and really almost with a sense of dedication that they gave up their practice and came back to school.

And I think in the 60s, with the tremendous expansion of the number of students, with the somewhat artificial encouragement for graduate work in planning, as indeed graduate work in all areas is a means of avoiding the draft,
I can't help but feel that the 60s saw a decline in, certainly, scholarship.
A decline in not only the scholarship, but in the direction that education was heading.
I think there was a lot of confusion in the 60s that
that caused a lot of reevaluation, both in the national planning profession groups and on the planning schools, that I think in many respects was perhaps healthy, but in many ways a waste of time.
I think certainly in the late 70s

for moving back more to, I think, higher levels of scholarship, with job prospects for graduating planners not necessarily assured that they're going to find what they're looking for in terms of the job planning.
Those that enter the planning profession, I think, are going to tend to be more dedicated, more sincere, rather than, as I'm afraid some of the 60s were just looking for a fabulous quick salary.
But I'm speaking from the outside of the educational system now, but certainly
interviewing the planners, I get the sense that we are beginning to see dedicated, qualified, well-trained planners available.
Roscoe, thank you very much for your time and for your thoughts.
I must thank you on the part of the Texas chapter of the American Planning Association and for the Department of Urban and Regional Planning at Texas A&M.
Well, I appreciate the opportunity to participate.
I think it's a marvelous program that you're undertaking.
And good luck in providing additional information.
Please call.
We'll probably be asking for some documents.
Let me give you here a listing of city planning publications of the department, which I tried to go back beyond the time that I came here and keep up to date.

Not only the formal publication, but a lot of the informal publications that hopefully a goodly number of these have gotten to the planning school libraries and are certainly available here in the department library.
Mighty fine.
This will be very useful.
Thank you.
